      <hedline>
        <hl1>Advice to G.O.P.: Veer to the Center; A Chance for Democrats</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Warren G Bovee letter, commenting on August 1 article on start of Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, says Democrats have chance to arouse public interest in their national convention in August by allowing delegates to nominate and choose party's vice presidential candidate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1):</p>
        <p>It is too late for the Republicans, but the Democrats still have a chance to arouse public interest in their national convention and in American politics.</p>
        <p>They can let their convention delegates nominate and choose the party's vice-presidential candidate.</p>
        <p>The nominating speeches, the suspense and excitement of the roll call of state delegations, the realization that it is the people and not merely a few political bosses who are choosing our potential leaders -- all of this might revive public interest in the campaigns and the election.</p>
        <p>And who is to say that the party delegates are incapable of choosing a good and electable candidate?</p>
        <p>WARREN G. BOVEE  Milwaukee, Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
